title: The Ai-Bitcoins Convergence
content:
The AI -Bitcoin Convergence: Reclaiming 
Your Agency in an Exponential Economy  
Finding agency in an AI -Bitcoin world: calm focus inside exponential change.  
"Am I about to be obsolete?"  
A friend asked me this over coffee recently. She's sharp, capable, always ahead of the curve. 
But her question wasn't just about work —it was about identity, belonging, and whether her 
hard-earned experience would still matter in a world run by algorithms.  
I didn't have a perfect answer. But I shared a framework that's been guiding me through 
decades of technological disruption —one that's working now more than ever.  
If you're feeling the weight of AI's acceleration, Bitcoin's mainstream moment, or the 
growing gap between exponential headlines and everyday reality, this is for you.  
The Speed Is Different This Time  
Every technological shift follows a pattern: fear first, then adaptation. I've leaned in with 
curiosity each time —the internet, mobile, cloud, blockchain, and now AI. I stayed hands -on, 
tested things myself, found my way through.  
But this cycle feels different. The speed is different. The stakes feel higher.  
We're living inside contradictory truths. AI is compressing time. Capital, capability, and 
competition are compounding faster than ever before. And yet, humans still wake up with 
families, feelings, and bills.  
The distance between exponential headlines and everyday life is where most people get 
lost—and it's also where opportunity hides.  
Last year, I explored how blockchain and AI could catalyse something bigger than just 
technology. Back then, it felt abstract, almost philosophical. Now, watching neighbours 
wrestle with ChatGPT while Bitcoin hits mainstream awareness, that intersection isn't 
theoretical —it's here.  
And most people are paralyzed instead of moving.  
That paralysis is expensive.  While people debate, early movers are already building their 
second or third experiment.  
The paralysis is what I want to help people break through. Because over the years, I've found 
a simple pattern that works for navigating exponential change —one that anyone can use:  
    Learn. Build. Own.  

The Frame That's Working for Me  
Over two decades of working inside technology's disruption, I noticed a pattern in my own 
learning. Whenever I first encountered something new, it often felt almost mystical —like it 
belonged to a world just out of reach.  
Instead of stepping back, I would challenge myself to try it, even when it seemed complex or 
intimidating.  
That act of moving from the abstract to the practical was what shifted everything for me. It 
wasn't about being fearless —it was about testing, fumbling, and learning through direct 
experience.  
Eventually, I realised that the approach guiding me through each wave of change could be 
distilled into three words: Learn. Build. Own.  
It sounds almost too simple. But for me, it meant shifting from consuming information to 
getting my hands dirty. Not because that's the "right" way —I know plenty of brilliant people 
who learn differently —but because I've realised I don't really understand something until I've 
wrestled with it myself.  
That's why blockchain finally clicked for me only after I moved beyond reading and started 
actively experimenting with it —transacting, investing, building, and seeing firsthand how the 
system worked.  
From Abstract to Practice  
I ignored blockchain technology for years. It seemed like noise, hype, something I could skip.  
Then in 2016, I read the Bitcoin whitepaper (published in 2008, but I came to it later). 
Something clicked. Not because I understood it all immediately —I didn't. But the elegance of 
the system, the way it solved trust without intermediaries, made me curious enough to try it 
myself.  
So I went through the then -difficult process of purchasing Bitcoin on -chain. I had to figure 
out exchanges, wallets, private keys, security. I learned what it actually meant to own 
something digital, to be responsible for it without a customer service numb er to call.  
Then came the NFT cycle —I minted things, collected things, learned what gave digital 
objects value and what didn't. The altcoin experimentation taught me about communities, 
speculation, and the difference between technology and narratives. I built small th ings, made 
mistakes, learned what worked and what didn't.  
That hands -on experience changed everything. Concepts that seemed abstract in articles 
became concrete through use. The headlines made more sense because I'd felt the friction 
myself.  
That's when I realised: the learning isn't in the consuming —it's in the doing.  

And now, I apply the same frame to AI and to life.  
What This Actually Looks Like Day -to-Day 
The Learn, Build, Own framework isn't abstract theory. Here's how it shows up in practice:  
Learning differently  
I've always had a generalist approach, moving across domains and connecting ideas in ways 
that don't fit neat categories. Recently, I needed to understand complex legislation and 
support mechanisms I'd never navigated before —the kind of situation where inf ormation 
feels deliberately obtuse.  
Using AI to parse legal documents, explain them in plain language, and surface the right 
questions —that's what rapid cross -domain learning looks like now. It's not about becoming 
an expert. It's about becoming capable enough to act.  
Building small things  
Experiments don't need to be impressive. They need to solve real problems. Managing a 
personal budget more effectively. Tracking health goals. Exploring new marketing 
opportunities.  
Each small build teaches you something about what actually works versus what just sounds 
clever. These aren't polished products —they're learning tools disguised as solutions.  
Owning the outcomes  
Multiple income streams aren't just about financial security. They're about having choices. 
When you rely on a single source of income, that source has power over your decisions.  
Building diverse value creation takes time and focus —but the foundation matters more 
than the pace.  
A Practical System for Limited Time  
This approach works with about 60-90 minutes of focused time weekly —whether that's 20 
minutes daily or a weekend deep dive. That's not a weakness —it's a boundary. And 
boundaries can make you sharper.  
Learn (20 -40 minutes when you can):  Pick one real input each week —something with 
substance, not just headlines. It could be a research paper, an investor earnings call, or a long -
form podcast. Drop the transcript into an AI model and let it help you summarise, surface the 
right questions, a nd connect dots to your world.  
Keep a running "learning journal" —even if it's messy notes on your phone or a single rolling 
Google Doc. Listen on a commute or walk; add three bullet insights after. Over time, those 
fragments compound into insight.  

Build (weekend experiments):  Tackle one small, real problem for yourself or someone close 
to you. Maybe it's setting up an AI budget tracker that categorises your spending, or a chatbot 
that reminds your teenager to submit their homework.  
The rule: it has to save at least 30 minutes of real effort. Don't worry if it's clunky —imperfect 
attempts teach faster than polished ones.  
Own (calculated exposure):  Hold Bitcoin in an amount that lets you sleep at night. If 
checking the price makes you anxious, you're over -allocated. Pair it with selective exposure 
to AI infrastructure —the companies building the chips, providing the energy, or running the 
systems tha t intelligence relies on.  
Write down why you're making each choice, and revisit it quarterly. That reflection is as 
valuable as the asset itself. The principle underneath: don't outsource your convictions to 
someone else's risk tolerance.  
The edge doesn't come from unlimited hours or perfect conditions —it comes from 
turning constraints into creativity and momentum.  
Why Bitcoin Matters in an AI World  
At first, AI and Bitcoin don't seem connected. But as more of our economy runs on AI, the 
link becomes obvious.  
AI shifts leverage to what software can't replicate:  
• The physical chips that run the models  
• The energy that powers them  
• The form of money no single government or company controls  
That's why Bitcoin is compelling. Not because it always goes up —it won't. But because when 
more of our commerce is mediated by algorithms, we need money that works on transparent 
rules anyone can verify.  
After two decades of technological centralisation —where every platform becomes a 
gatekeeper —Bitcoin feels like part of the antidote. It's infrastructure that can't be controlled 
by any single entity.  
What's Happening Beneath the Headlines  
Here's what I'm watching that signals something real is happening beneath the noise:  
Energy markets:  AI's biggest constraint isn't software —it's electricity. U.S. data centre 
power demand is forecast to more than double by 2035, from 35GW to 78GW —that's 8.6% 
of national consumption. To put that in perspective, that's roughly equivalent to adding the 
entire power consumption of Argentina to U.S. data centres alone. This is why tech 
companies are now competing with cities for power contracts.  

Capital flows:  In 2024, $11.5B was invested in crypto and blockchain startups, with 
infrastructure receiving the most attention.  
Hardware diffusion:  As AI shifts from data centres into phones and cars, it means everyone 
will need new devices —creating waves of upgrades we haven't seen since smartphones first 
appeared. Apple's integration of AI chips in the iPhone 15 Pro signals this shift from cloud to  
edge.  
The infrastructure story is the opposite of the headlines. While news screams "overvaluation," 
the builders are quietly saying: "we don't have enough capacity yet."  
Both can be true.  
Navigating the Uncomfortable Middle  
White -collar roles are feeling pressure before they disappear. Talented professionals are 
questioning whether their skills still matter. The instinct is either panic or denial. Neither 
works.  
The edge now lies in what AI can't yet replicate: judgment, taste, and context.  Knowledge 
is abundant. Meaning is scarce.  
Here's a starting point: tell your favourite AI model, "Here's what I'm good at." Ask it to 
design a 30 -day plan for turning that skill into something tangible. Then test one version of it 
publicly—even if it's rough.  
The learning isn't in the planning. It's in the doing.  
Your Next Moves  
If this resonates, here's where to start:  
• Block 30 minutes a day  for focused AI learning. Choose one substantive source each 
week and use AI to summarise, highlight questions, and tie it back to your context.  
• Run one small weekend experiment.  Solve a real problem for yourself or someone 
close; aim to save 30+ minutes of effort.  
• Think in terms of allocations —money, time, attention —sized to your comfort.  
• Write down your reasoning.  Revisit quarterly, not daily. Adjust based on what 
you've learned.  
• Find your people.  Monthly conversations with others in AI & crypto matter as much 
as the tools —they create accountability and momentum.  
The Real Question  
The question isn't whether AI and crypto will transform everything —they already are. The 
question is whether you'll move through this as an observer, or as someone shaping your own 
outcomes.  

We're living through a moment where technology serves both practical needs and something 
larger. The tools to participate are more accessible than ever. The barriers to entry keep 
falling.  
The only question is whether we'll use this moment to create agency —or just consume 
content about others creating it.  
Learn what matters. Build what lasts. Own your truth.  
That's how I'm navigating exponential change —not just for myself, but for the people and 
futures I care about.  
And maybe, for you too.  
 
This is not financial advice —it's agency advice.  
 
What's your first experiment going to be?  I'd love to hear what resonates with your 
journey—drop a comment below and let's start the conversation.  
 
References & Supporting Sources:  
1. Bitcoin Whitepaper (2008)  
2. Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance - Bitcoin Mining Sustainability  
3. Bloomberg NEF - AI Data Centre Energy Forecasts  
4. McKinsey: Data Centres and AI's Power Hunger  
 
LinkedIn Promotional Post  
"Am I about to be obsolete?"  
A friend asked me this over coffee. Sharp, capable, successful —and genuinely wondering if 
her decades of experience would matter in a world run by algorithms.  
She's not alone in feeling this.  
AI is compressing time. Bitcoin is going mainstream. And the gap between exponential 
headlines and everyday reality? That's where most people freeze.  
But here's what I've learned through 20+ years of riding these waves —from the internet to 
mobile to cloud to blockchain to now:  

The paralysis is more expensive than the mistakes.  
While people debate, early movers are already building their second or third experiment.  
I spent years ignoring blockchain. Then I read the Bitcoin whitepaper in 2016. Something 
clicked—not because I understood it all, but because I got curious enough to try it myself. 
That shift from consuming to doing changed everything.  
Now I use the same framework for AI and everything that matters:  
    Learn. Build. Own.  
It's not about unlimited hours or perfect conditions. It's about 60 -90 focused minutes a week. 
It's about small experiments that save real time. It's about calculated exposure that lets you 
sleep at night.  
The infrastructure beneath these headlines tells a different story than the panic: U.S. data 
centre power demand will more than double by 2035. $11.5B flowed into crypto 
infrastructure in 2024. AI is moving from clouds to your pocket.  
The edge lies in what AI can't replicate: judgment, taste, and context.  
Knowledge is abundant. Meaning is scarce.  
So here's my question for you: Are you positioning yourself to shape outcomes, or just 
watching them happen?  
I wrote about the practical framework I'm using to navigate this —not theory, but the actual 
day-to-day approach that's working.

title: Navigating-Ai-And-Crypto-As-The-Markets-Tell-Two-Different-Stories
content:
Making  Sense  of the Shift:  How  I'm 
Navigating  AI and Crypto  as the 
Markets  Tell Two Different  Stories  
 
 
 
 
Nicola  Harvey   
 
Empowering women, creatives, NFP’s & startups in crypto, blockchain & AI. Strategic consultant, 
opportunity architect & visionary entrepreneur making tech accessible and maximising growth 
potential.  
 
Publish Date: September 21, 2025  
 
I've been deep in crypto trading since 2016 and building extensively with AI since 
2023. What I'm seeing now has me both excited and concerned.  
The gap between real innovation and market hype has never felt wider.  
On one hand, there's incredible innovation happening. AI tools that genuinely 
transform how we work and blockchain applications solving real problems. On the 
other hand, market valuations and headlines feel completely disconnected from what 
I'm experiencin g day -to-day. 
So I've been doing what I tend to do when things feel uncertain: researching 
historical patterns to make sense of where we might be heading. Not because I have 
all the answers, but because understanding these cycles helps me make better 
decisions about whe re to invest my time and money.  
Why I'm Sharing This Now  


For years, I've kept my research, insights, and learnings about these technologies 
within a close circle of friends and family. But recently, I've made the decision to start 
sharing my ideas and thought processes more broadly.  
The more I engage with AI and blockchain technologies, the more convinced I 
become that we need diverse voices and perspectives shaping how these tools 
develop and get implemented. There's immense value in having people approach 
these spaces from different  backgrounds, with different priorities, and different 
definitions of what constitutes meaningful progress.  
I'm sharing not because I have all the answers, but because I believe there's 
tremendous opportunity for more people, particularly women, to bring their unique 
perspectives and capabilities to this space.  
The conversations happening about these technologies are still largely dominated by 
the same voices, but the real breakthroughs often come from people who see 
applications and possibilities that others miss.  
The Real Innovation Happening Below the Hype  
Let me start with what's actually working in my world.  
I first started studying prompt engineering back in 2023 when I got genuinely excited 
about AI's potential for improving everyday lives and providing opportunities for 
creative potential. Since then, I've been experimenting with AI in several ways:  
• Part of creating a proprietary content marketing system (currently in trial)   
• Supporting a global AI blockchain project for several months   
• Leading AI implementation in the humanitarian sector   
• Developing personal assistants and custom GPTs  
In the crypto space, I'm seeing blockchain applications that have moved far beyond 
speculation: supply chain transparency, digital identity verification, fair compensation 
systems for creators. These are solving real problems for real businesses and 
individuals.  
But here's  what  concerns  me: the gap between what's actually useful and what's 
getting the attention (and investment dollars) is feeling wider than ever.  
 

What 150 Years of Tech Cycles Taught Me About Today's 
Markets  
When I studied Ray Dalio's "The Changing World Order" back in 2021, it gave me a 
framework for understanding how innovation cycles actually unfold. The technology 
itself is often transformative, but the market's initial response is usually... enthusiastic 
to the point of being disconnected from reality.  
That framework stuck with me, so recently I found myself researching other pivotal 
technological moments such as electricity, automobiles, computers, the internet. I 
wanted to understand how these transitions actually played out, not just the success 
stories, but the whole messy process of adoption, speculation, correction, and 
eventual integration.  
What  struck  me was how similar  the patterns  are: 
Electricity:  It took over 40 years from Edison's first power plant in 1882 for electricity 
to reach half of American homes, despite massive initial investment and hype.  
Automobiles:  Hundreds of car companies emerged in the early 1900s with wild 
speculation driving valuations, yet only a handful survived to become the giants we 
know today.  
The Internet:  The dot -com boom saw the NASDAQ rise 600% between 1995 -2000, 
then crash spectacularly, but the underlying technology continued to transform 
everything, just more gradually than the initial hysteria predicted.  
Every major technological shift seems to follow this cycle: initial skepticism  → 
explosive hype and speculation → disappointment when reality doesn't match 
expectations → finally, years later, genuine transformation that's more profound but 
also more subtle than anyone originally predicted.  
Looking at the data now, I'm seeing familiar patterns: concentration of market gains 
in a handful of tech stocks, valuations that assume instant total transformation, the 
"this time is different" narrative that accompanies every major innovation cycle.  
I'm not saying this to be pessimistic… actually quite the opposite. These patterns help 
me understand where we likely are in the cycle and how to position accordingly.  
Why I'm Playing Two Different Games Simultaneously  
The unsettling feeling I have about the markets has led me to think about this in two 
distinct timeframes, and I'm being quite intentional about separating them.  

Short -term focus: Market positioning  
I'm still allocating what I can to crypto because my research suggests we might be 
positioned for meaningful gains in the coming months. With Bitcoin around $112K -
$117K and most supply currently profitable, it feels like we're in late -stage territory 
where  things could get really interesting.  
While analysts are setting targets in the $150K -$250K range, my own charting 
suggests more conservative levels around $140K -$150K before I'd want to 
reevaluate, though I'm very aware that risk is getting higher.  
I'm watching these next three months closely. While institutional adoption has 
changed some dynamics, the traditional cycle patterns I've studied are showing 
signals that make me cautious.  
Long -term focus: Building real value  
This is where my real energy goes, engaging with the actual technology, being part 
of the real innovation happening in this space, and growing my skillset in these 
emerging technologies.  
I'm working to broaden my understanding so I can take a more strategic approach, 
not just for supporting myself, but for the people around me and those who employ 
or engage me for my knowledge and expertise.  
The key for me is keeping these two approaches completely separate. The 
speculative side is about timing and market psychology. The technology side is 
about building lasting value and capability.  
The Numbers That Are Actually Driving My Decisions  
Here are some of the data points shaping my thinking:  
From  an innovation  perspective:  The AI market reached $391 billion in 2025, and 
the productivity improvements I'm seeing firsthand support genuine value creation. 
Small businesses report saving 10 -15 hours weekly through AI automation, and 
creative professionals are completing projects 4 0% faster.  
From  an economic  perspective:  Things are more complex. US household debt hit 
$18.39 trillion with delinquency rates at 4.4%. Here in Australia, unemployment rose 
to 4.3% in August 2025, even as tech valuations soar.  

This isn't about being bearish or bullish, it's about recognising that the real economy 
and financial markets are telling different stories right now.  
The 80% Gender Gap That's Creating Massive Opportunity  
One thing that consistently frustrates me is how male -dominated the conversation 
around these technologies remains. In Australia, men hold over 80% of crypto's 
value, and the AI discussion is similarly skewed.  
But here's  what  I've learned:  the best opportunities often emerge when we focus 
on utility rather than speculation. While others chase the next 10x return, we can 
build sustainable competitive advantages by actually mastering these tools.  
The women I know who are succeeding in this space aren't trying to time markets or 
pick winning stocks. They're systematically building skills, automating workflows, and 
creating value for their clients, employers and businesses in ways that weren't 
possib le five years ago.  
My 4 -Part Framework for Navigating the Next 18 Months  
Based on everything I'm seeing, here's how I'm thinking about the near future:  
1. Balanced  approach  to opportunities:  I'm continuing to evaluate market 
movements and technological developments, but putting equal energy into building 
practical skills. Understanding where opportunities might emerge is important, but 
so is being prepared to act on them with real capabilities  rather than just speculation.  
2. Practical  implementation  over  hype:  Every AI tool I adopt has to solve a genuine 
problem and demonstrably improve my work or save time. I'm interested in cutting -
edge developments, but my focus is on what actually works today.  
3. Strategic  diversification:  Whether it's learning new technologies, developing 
different income streams, or understanding various market sectors, I'm spreading 
both risk and opportunity across multiple areas. The goal is resilience without 
missing significant shifts.  
4. Community  and knowledge  sharing:  The women who are navigating this 
successfully are sharing research, collaborating on practical applications, and 
supporting each other through uncertainty. There's too much happening too quickly 
to figure it all out alone.  
 
Why the Best Opportunities Come After the Hype Dies Down  
Here's what I'm most excited about: I think we're approaching a period where these 
technologies become more accessible and practical, not less. When speculative 

attention moves on to the next shiny object, the tools and infrastructure will still be 
there… probably better and cheaper than they are today.  
The entrepreneurs who spend this time learning, building, and creating genuine 
value will be positioned incredibly well when the dust settles.  
This isn't about trying to predict the future or time markets perfectly. It's about 
building skills and systems that create value regardless of what happens with 
valuations or market sentiment.  
From Solo Research to Collaborative Discovery  
I'm honestly still figuring a lot of this out as I go. The technology keeps evolving 
faster than I can sometimes keep up with, the market signals are often contradictory, 
and I find myself constantly re -evaluating whether I'm interpreting things correctly.  
But here's what I'm discovering: the shift from keeping my research private to 
engaging in open dialogue has been incredibly energising. Having conversations 
with other entrepreneurs who are wrestling with similar questions, comparing notes 
on which AI too ls actually deliver versus which ones are just clever marketing, or 
working through investment decisions when every headline seems designed to 
create confusion rather than clarity, has revealed insights I never would have reached 
on my own.  
The collaborative aspect of this exploration is proving far more valuable than I 
anticipated. When someone shares how they're using a tool I've been struggling 
with, or when we can decode market signals together that individually left us 
confused, there's this creative energy that emerges.  
I'm genuinely excited about the possibility of more of these exchanges, because I'm 
seeing firsthand how much faster we all learn when we're sharing this exploration.  
If you're  navigating  similar  shifts  and contradictions  in your  world,  I'd 
genuinely  love to hear  how you're  approaching  it. Not only to learn from your 
perspective, but because I suspect we'll both discover something new in the 
conversation that neither of us would have found alone.  
These are complex times that require collective wisdom more than individual 
brilliance.  

This piece  reflects  my personal  experiences  and perspectives  as someone  building  at 
the intersection  of technology  and traditional  markets.  Nothing  here constitutes  
financial  advice—I'm simply  offering  one approach  to making  sense  of a complex  and 
rapidly  evolving  landscape.  
#WomenInTech  #AIStrategy  #CryptoTrading  #TechLeadership  
#WomenEntrepreneurs
